emmeline pankhurst is the woman of the day;

text:
a live durational performance by colombian- born artist, nathalie alfonso, entitled ‚Äú underscore,‚Äù an incessant rhythm of washing away her own work that visualizes invisible labor along the facade of fair market.

last december during miami art week, @anthony_spinello and @zoelukov curated the first in a series of alternative art fairs, entitled ‚Äúfair.‚Äù fair., an alternative non-commercial art fair that took place december 7-10, 2017 at brickell city centre, served as a platform for a diverse and multigenerational group of women artists. fair. seeked to address gender inequality in the art world and beyond by providing space for radical women artists to create site-specific interventions in a non-traditional venue.

photo: diana larrea / @parcialmentenublada

text:
" i have been finding it really hard to put my thoughts into words. it‚Äôs often confusing and confronting and difficult to address the abuse or the sexism you have faced, but haven‚Äôt had the courage to publicly address for so long.

like most other victims/survivors, i blamed myself for a long time.

the men i want to write about today are sajid khan, zain durrani, and vikas bahl.

before i tell you what happened with me, i want people to remember that #metoo isn‚Äôt about hollywood or bollywood‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääit‚Äôs about you being able to speak up about people that have abused you, it‚Äôs about sexism, it‚Äôs about you having a voice and not being scared to address the people that think it‚Äôs okay to misuse their power over you. it‚Äôs about not blaming yourself.

industries like these help because they are in the limelight. the media doesn‚Äôt always want to cover it when it‚Äôs your father or your uncle, and that‚Äôs the harsh truth. but the fact that famous people are being named, is supposed to give you the courage to speak up. for years, girls have been trying to speak up‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääoften, they‚Äôre silenced. but today this movement is supposed to help you come out with your stories. whether its a family member or a friend or a co worker or an ex lover or a current partner or just a one off date‚Ää‚Äî‚Äätell someone you trust. speak about the abuse. don‚Äôt let all the attention that‚Äôs been given to the film industries take away from your story. your story may not make it in the news, but people, all over this country are only trying to cover the stories of these famous people to give you the courage to speak. i, today, am talking about my story to remind you, that so can you.

because i didn‚Äôt know where to begin, and who to begin with, i‚Äôm going to begin right at the start and hope you stay till the end. "
- @redheadwayfarer

text:
for those who are still unaware about the allegations faced by co founder of @ttt_official.
we are sharing this post to support shrutee choudhary and others who came out bravely. below is the full post by shrutee. .
dear chintan (@thethirdalphabet),
. 
you came to me at a point in my life when i was already too broken, but you had a soft spot for broken souls, didn‚Äôt you tell me? that first night, when you‚Äôd ‚Äòdiscovered‚Äô my ‚Äòwriting‚Äô on instagram, we spoke for hours. i thought we connected, and i‚Äôd been longing for a soulful connection ever since my heart had still been intact. so i opened up to you, slowly, gradually over many spontaneous meetings, and extremely poetic conversations. i wouldn‚Äôt lie when i say the first few moments didn‚Äôt feel magical. when you shared your story with me, and as did i. the silence was still comforting and there was an innocence to our bond ‚Äì we used to hold hands for so long. maybe, i idealised you into a someone who was completely different from the real version. or maybe for that brief moment, you were really being genuine. i don‚Äôt know. it‚Äôs tough to say now. the memory of our first kiss is vague. but i remember the feeling, and don‚Äôt you claim to be all about that too? you said you hadn‚Äôt felt so strongly for someone in a long time and how could i not believe you ‚Äì you seemed like a dream come true of sorts. you were that one person i unraveled my wounded soul to, you were a place of trust.

and then we had scotland. do you remember what you‚Äôd told me before we left? that you wouldn‚Äôt even touch me if i was uncomfortable, that you respect me too much and you care. cut to the first night in that bedroom, you were already on top of me. i said no. you apologised and admitted to the fact that it‚Äôs hard to control the urges around me. again, brownie points for making me feel special. then you tried again, i said no, again. it wounded your ego and you faced away from me in the far corner of the bed, making me feel like shit, stained in guilt, extremely uncomfortable.
.
continued in comments.
.

.

text:
üîî gender-based violence installation.

this installation focused on those who has ever been violated. we made a huge muted bell out of paper plates.

a bell is usually used to call a community together or to warn them from danger.

this bell is muted.

the muted bell represents the voices that has been silenced and unacknowledged with regards to gender based violence.

the uct community was urged to write their story of how they were violated whether it was physical, emotional of vocal (such as cat calling). this artwork was a great success with stories written all over which is very sad an unfortunate.

thank you for everyone respecting the cause and for those participating.

#genderbasedviolence #metoo #menaretrash #installationart #conceptart #conceptualart #art #change

text:
dear "woke" feminists (you know who you are)

you looked the other way when women - young and old, endured lecherous behaviour from men in power, even when you knew what was going on... guess it's easy to be a publically woke feminist - giving gyaan, shaming people's limited knowledge, when the odds aren't against you. these women were brave af to continue to produce amazing work and put up with such behaviour from the men who violated them, and from people like you, who could have helped stop it.

now that the world is watching, take cognizance of your inaction, and for once be the woke feminist you pretended to be, and investigate all the alleged perpetrators.

text:
i believe most of us can to relate to the following story submission in one way or another, unfortunately. the writer has chosen to remain anonymous.

i was about 19 when one day i boarded a public bus in my hometown. the bus was practically empty, but this man came and sat next to me. the bus hadn't still started to move when he started playing something on his mobile phone, and it seemed like be was trying to show it to me. i saw from the corner of my eye that it was a porn clip. i froze for a bit and didn't know how to react. but then i found my voice and told him to sit somewhere else. he just got off the bus. so i guess that's all he came on the bus for. there have been other times when my breasts and waist have been touched in crowded buses. unfortunately that time i just felt that this is normal because every girl has to put up with this. i have undergone harassment in my home as well. my maths tutor used to touch my arm from time to time while teaching, my art teacher used to hug me on the pretext of applauding me. i could tell something was wrong, i didn't feel comfortable. but as i always thought, this is how people show affection. now that i hear all these stories of different people, i am glad that at least one of my parents always stayed home when i had home tutors coming over. they were concerned about my safety.

text:
üîî gender-based violence installation.

this installation focused on those who has ever been violated. we made a huge muted bell out of paper plates.

a bell is usually used to call a community together or to warn them from danger.

this bell is muted.

the muted bell represents the voices that has been silenced and unacknowledged with regards to gender based violence.

the uct community was urged to write their story of how they were violated whether it was physical, emotional of vocal (such as cat calling). this artwork was a great success with stories written all over which is very sad an unfortunate.

thank you for everyone respecting the cause and for those participating.

#genderbasedviolence #metoo #menaretrash #installationart #conceptart #conceptualart #art #change

it's unfortunate that a picture of 'vastra harana' by  lord krishna is being cicrculated in social media and the gopis have been tagged with #metoo. lord krishna is being protrayed as a molester. judging an incident which took place thousand of years ago without having concrete knowledge about the society of that time is nothing but foolishness. this futile attempt becomes a laughable stock when people with limited knowledge judge lord krishna who stands beyond any words, expressions and intellects. again these pseudo-intellectuals are spinning the facts to  justify their malicious intention of maligning and diluting hinduism by raising suspicion among the followers. the act of vastra harana by lord krishna was a metaphorical one, which distinguishes between reality and illusions. the worldly possessions like clothes and ornaments can be compared with illusions. again it can be taken as a childish prank of bal-gopal as he was just 6/7 years old then. our feminists have used the picture of a young krishna instead of the child-krishna. the depiction of vastra harana doesn't have any kind of explicit or implicit sexual connotations. they have trickily overlooked this aspect of the scriptural description. most importantly all the gopis were in immensely love with lord krishna. it was clearly evident when with their mothers' permission, they performed katyani vrata to get lord krishna as their husband. finally these feminists need to remember that it's the sole prerogative of a lady to decide whether an incident comes under the #metoo moment or not ! if gopis had no problems, then you are a nobody to interfere in their personal affairs. that's probably a real form women empowerment.
#lordkrishna #hinduism #metoo #india #iskcon

text:
no one can prepare you for the first time he grabs you. the panic attack that ensues as your skin crawls from feeling his fingers on your body once again. no one will tell you how long it takes to get over the feeling of being violated. no one tells you that you never can and you never will. no one warns you that three years later, when you wake up from a nightmare, it will feel like you have been assaulted all over again. that sometimes when your boyfriend‚Äôs hands near your neck, you want to cry, but you fake a moan instead.

no one will tell you that you will never forget that night. that you will never forget his face. the sounds of your screams as you begged him to stop. or the feeling of his hands forcing themselves on your body, pulling at you, scarring you for years to come.

no one will prepare you for the accusations. the lies. the threats. the questions about your character or your choice of clothing. no one will tell you about the injustice. the silence. the lack of consequence.

no one will tell you that you will have to fight like hell to prove it. this is who you are now. a walking statistic. just another number with a pulse. you‚Äôre not unique. this happens every day to thousands of women. and you‚Äôre just like them. that‚Äôs what people¬†will¬†tell you. but no one will tell you the truth. no one will prepare you.

text: my lovely and wonderful friend @jackiejoymanely_inspired helped me change it up a little. we took out some dark and brought in the light. here‚Äôs a little before and after along with a little inspo for this lovely friday. let‚Äôs start taking care of ourselves without feeling guilty. this is something i am starting to work on. telling myself i am not being selfish to take a little time for myself , doing things that make me feel beautiful and happy. we give so much of ourselves to our jobs, home life and our kids that we tend to forget about us and our mental health and well being. so take some time for you. get you hair, nails, lashes or whatever done. go get coffee with a friend or by yourself. take some time to disconnect from life and reconnect with your inner self.  #maketimeforyou #youarenotbeingselfish

so while i have had my #metoo experiences which most who don‚Äôt have powerful parents from the particular industry go thru that is not what this post is about ..
.i said no every single time and with god‚Äôs blessing each time i was allowed to leave without even a nail being touched...(of course i never got those projects )....
i am in support of people who speak up for justice wether it be a man or a woman......anyone who wants to work in a line that is their passion should be allowed to work on merit of talent and hard work üôèüèª
i have known guys who have gone thru it too!
sexual misconduct is not only toward women....
also i have seen quite a few women willing to do anything to make it.....and somewhere i do wish they,d stop so that everyone had a fair chance and then men would maybe not presume all women are willing ....
and i have also met many good people in this line too...respectable and respecting people who never ever crossed the line üôèüèªand even though i was told i‚Äôd never make it by people i said no to i did work with my values intact (whatever little work i have done )...
but even though my experiences were nothing compared to the horrific cases i‚Äôm reading about i still developed an anxiety and panic attack problem because of everything i saw from a young age ...
at one point my panic and anxiety was so bad that for the longest time i couldn‚Äôt even go to an office for a meeting if the producer or director was a man!.
so this post is about being an anxiety and panic attack survivor ü§òüèª ....#im #notashamed nor should you be if you suffer from #panic #anxiety #stress or #depression .
i healed fully and so can youüôèüèªüåàüíûüíû
p.s pls be kind to people speaking up about their traumas ...it takes guts and a long time to heal mentally and emotionally !üôèüèª

text: i know my post yesterday was really heavy but it was also incredibly necessary, for me and all the other women out there that needed to see it. the amount of women that wrote me to tell me they had similar experiences when they were younger/in high school was astounding and while it makes my heart heavy to hear those stories i also felt incredibly honored to have been told them, so thank you, from the bottom of my heart. let's all take a moment to stand and raise our glass to every one of the profoundly amazing women of this world. i have no doubt that we will take this place by the shoulders, shake it with our ferocious strength and change it for the better, one story at a time. because you and i, we belong to a sisterhood that can never be broken. i love you all with every ounce of my being and i am so proud to be part of that sisterhood üëµüèΩüë©üèæ‚Äç‚öïÔ∏èüë©üèø‚Äçüéìüë©üèª‚Äçüè´üë©üèΩ‚Äç‚öñüë©üèº‚Äçüîßüë©üèª‚Äçüíºüë©üèø‚Äçüî¨üë≥üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüßïüèæ #believewomen #womensreality #believesurvivors #metoo #whyididntreport #imwithher #timesup #womenoftheworld #sisterhood #momentsinmotherhood #inspiremothers #honestlymothering #parenthood_unveiled #memoirsofmotherhood #therealparenthood #theeverymother #badasssmothers

text:
you asked me how i feel about my harassment. its really difficult to put it into words.
i feel like cutting those parts of my body that has ever been touched. i feel like a filthy whore because someone has touched me. 
i spend my nights wide awake at night staring at my ceiling, reliving the moment he pushed himself inside me without my permission and how much did it hurt. how it destroyed not only my body but my soul aswell.

no one could have prepared you for the shame you felt as you grabbed your clothes and your belongings and wnet to home, as bruises started to colour your body.

text: i‚Äôve had a second account dedicated to issues like these for a while now, but i‚Äôve decided to merge my main with my activist account because this is who i am, these are the issues i believe in. this is what i want to see change in our world. if you don‚Äôt agree with me on some issues that‚Äôs okay, say something, speak out, comment on my post and let‚Äôs have a discussion, maybe we can both learn something through constructive debate. and if you do agree with me just know that you‚Äôre not alone. the past couple years i‚Äôve felt really hopeless, and it‚Äôs only been magnified as of recent. there are millions of others who want to see the same productive, inclusive, positive change that you do. but that change isn‚Äôt going to happen just by scrolling through social media, reading articles and watching videos that infuriate you. ignoring those articles and videos won‚Äôt help either, the fact that some people can ignore certain issues is a privilege, recognize that. change is only going to come about through acting on your beliefs. get out there and register to vote, that goes for people on all sides of these issues. voting is our right and not everyone on this planet has that power in their government. so take advantage of it, let your opinions be heard ‚Äòround the world, it‚Äôs waiting and listening.

we aren't done folks! join us on november at the #imready conference to explore what it means to be self-identified aapi women as it relates to different forms of gender-based violence.
.
joining us is hamida yusufzai. hamida has served with banteay srei since 2016. she has also worked internationally as a community organizer, a rape crisis advocate and a consultant for law enforcement - she has a global understanding of violence against women. she currently instructs a reality based self-defense class in oakland, on her own time. she has over 15 years of experience working in youth organizing with system impacted people of color. she is an advocate for comprehensive services for commercial sexual exploitation of children (csec) and contributes to the enhancement of the intensive case management component used to address the economic and emotional needs of southeast asian young women and girls. learn more about hamida's work @banteaysreioakland
.
registration ends 10/22!! link in bio!

text:
today i took a mental health day. i'm not sick, i'm not insane, i just needed a day to put my broken pieces back in place, because although i'm strong, i'm also vulnerable, and all that is going on in terms of women's rights is a constant trigger. i'm reliving almost on a daily basis my own trauma and i just needed a day to find my balance, my inner peace, my harmony. it's important to practice self-care. remember and repeat: you are worthy, you are valuable, you are strong, you deserve respect and love.

text:
this is how we go on. 
every friday i get an email from @austinkleon. it is one of my favourite things in my inbox. i loved his steal like an artist and show your work and i look forward to the next book coming out soon. 
he inspires me to keep going, keep doing, keep giving, keep listening, keep showing up, keep writing, keep doing the work. 
what a doozy of a season. what an invitation for us to rise and rise and keep rising. 
i may go quiet for a while, i may take time out to restore and refresh. but this party is not over yet. hell, no. 
i will keep speaking up, keep leaning in, keep learning, keep unlearning, keep deconstructing, keep decolonizing, keep hoping and keep loving. 
it is no coincidence that you and i are here, at this time in history. we have beautiful and good work to do. 
reminds me of toni morrison‚Äôs words: this is¬†precisely¬†the time when artists go to work. there is no time for despair, no place for self-pity, no need for silence, no room for fear. we speak, we write, we do language. that is how civilizations heal.‚Äù ‚Äîtoni morrison 
amen.

text:
i am so thankful 9 months ago i decided to make a tough decision. 
i left a good company that i had build sustainable residual income at for 5 years, for something that has truly given me life!! i left something that i was comfortable in, for something that has breathed excitement, belief and joy into my life. 
was it a scary jump? heck yes.... but it was all worth it! 
i am inspired daily to pursue better, and to achieve my goals and dreams. 
i am surrounded by the most incredible people, and have met some of my best friends in the process. 
don‚Äôt settle for good,
pursue greatness. 
don‚Äôt settle for comfort 
pursue scary, hard, and fear ! 
it is on the other side of the great unknown, where greatness lies !

text:
ever since the #metoo movement began, and i have been reading harrowing accounts of people and recollecting my own experiences, of sexual assaults, hurt, harm, pain, violence that we have been causing to each other, it feels like a knife ripping my chest and heart apart, and this thought has occupied my mind-are we so in control of other humans, or so not in control of ourselves, that we start doing anything and eveything with an other person?

think of this! 
aren't each of us a fragile flower? don't we want and love to be treated like one? 
nature has the answers to our issues, if only we care to look and observe. how nice would it be if we could learn the art of peaceful co-existence from them, the flowers, the leaves, the plants and the trees? 
#flowers #colours #green #pink #grass #naturephotography #peace #metoo

text:
last few days have been really disturbing for every women in india. this is because #metoo movement has finally picked up pace in here.
and i feel somewhat ambivalent about it.
though i'm extremely happy for the women who finally feel secure and confident to talk about sexual harassment sexual abuse they faced years ago. i think it's courageous of them to do this. and i
have immense amount of love and respect for each and every one of them.
but i think it's equally disturbing and disgusting how many women have gone through this shit in their life.
it's shameful that even in 21st century we are unable to provide women a safe and sound environment.
the stories we are hearing and reading are heartbreaking..
india has once again failed its women.
at the end i just wanna say one thing no matter where woman work, what work she does, what clothes she wear.
no women should be exploited. 
ending the silence!

#nomeansno
#metoo #sexualabuse #sexualharassment #indiametoomovement #women #createsafeenvironmentforwomen
#women #saynotorapes #indiawomen

text:
this is tremendously sad. when a child is abused they carry it for life. and even when they battle the demons and move forward, the experiences are set in the foundation of their development. it‚Äôs never forgotten. and no one deserves that. some don‚Äôt even get the help they need and that is even more heartbreaking. all these stories need to be heard. and justice should be brought to all victims.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
my new project, our stories matter, is a way for all of us to be heard. victims of assault, abuse, and domestic violence have voices and we need to listen and support them. i‚Äôve also teamed up with licensed psychotherapist @cosmicchristine to help provide a safe place for people to come forward and open up.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
we are currently accepting submissions for the project. sharing your story not only can be therapeutic, but can help others with healing. and you can be anonymous if it makes you more comfortable. this collaborative journal will be real, raw, eye-opening, heartbreaking, and inspirational. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
you can learn more at ourstoriesmatter.info

so while i have had my #metoo experiences which most who don‚Äôt have powerful parents from the particular industry go thru that is not what this post is about ..
.i said no every single time and with god‚Äôs blessing each time i was allowed to leave without even a nail being touched...(of course i never got those projects )....
i am in support of people who speak up for justice wether it be a man or a woman......anyone who wants to work in a line that is their passion should be allowed to work on merit of talent and hard work üôèüèª
i have known guys who have gone thru it too!
sexual misconduct is not only toward women....
also i have seen quite a few women willing to do anything to make it.....and somewhere i do wish they,d stop so that everyone had a fair chance and then men would maybe not presume all women are willing ....
and i have also met many good people in this line too...respectable and respecting people who never ever crossed the line üôèüèªand even though i was told i‚Äôd never make it by people i said no to i did work with my values intact (whatever little work i have done )...
but even though my experiences were nothing compared to the horrific cases i‚Äôm reading about i still developed an anxiety and panic attack problem because of everything i saw from a young age ...
at one point my panic and anxiety was so bad that for the longest time i couldn‚Äôt even go to an office for a meeting if the producer or director was a man!.
so this post is about being an anxiety and panic attack survivor ü§òüèª ....#im #notashamed nor should you be if you suffer from #panic #anxiety #stress or #depression .
i healed fully and so can youüôèüèªüåàüíûüíû
p.s pls be kind to people speaking up about their traumas ...it takes guts and a long time to heal mentally and emotionally !üôèüèª

text:
"just get over it" they say... this is what i have to say about the #stopkavanaugh movement.. first of all, whoever put this on their vehicle in the sunset, thank you for speaking out! i feel supported i feel heard! 
i also want to take a minute and recognize a very serious issue in our world, #sexualassault and #domesticviolence  as a multiple incident survivor this topic does not come lightly for me to discuss. to me it is disturbing that it took some allegations of one person to come out in the media for people to all of a sudden start caring when its been happening for centuries. people like myself and other survivors have yelled out and spoken out and i've never received the recognition or restitution for what has happened. so shame on humanity for just now seeing the problem! if a woman comes out about what happened to her #believeher #believesurvivors it is not a joke and it is something we must carry our whole lives and fight out of our minds our whole lives. 
stop the b.s. and stand for survivors because one day it could happen to you and then what? oh and p.s. never tell a survivor to simply "get over it" if it were that easy we would.

text:
domestic violence 
in south asia, the rigid cultures and discriminatory attitudes towards women have led to the exploitation of women, from individual to community levels. women and girls in this region are exposed to biased, inequitable practices and violent behaviors at all stages of life. the high incidence of female infanticide in india, the frequent incidence of culture-specific types of violence like honor killings, acid attacks, and stove burnings in bangladesh, trafficking of women from nepal, sri-lanka and india to other regions of world, forced into prostitution and other forms of sexual violence, as well as the high prevalence of domestic violence in all countries of the region, all constitute examples of violence against women in this region. the deeply entrenched cultural norms, lead to acceptance of violence as ‚Äònormal life experiences for a woman‚Äô and to dispel such cultural myths and norms is a formidable task. in the family unit the man is the undisputed ruler of the household. the ineffective legislations encourage abusers to commit abusive acts against women without any repercussions. to eradicate violence against women in this region there are some fundamental challenges which include: changing existing social and individual attitudes, both at the family and societal levels, as well as implementation of policies for equity and sustaining of the political will to achieve significant results.

text:
read the caption .
.
.
you know what's the biggest nightmare for a girl is that she will get raped. you give respect you get respect . it is the most important thing to anyone in this world. but do people actually respect girls? 
in india rape is the fourth most common crime . according to ncrb (national crime records bureau)2013 there was approx.25000 rapes . u.s.a , sweden , france , canada , ethiopia, sri lanka , uk , germany are the top ten countries in the matter of rape.
are you still thinking of "save girl child" let's start a new one "make this world a better place for girl's".
why the girls are said to behave with decency ? why the girls are stopped to wear short dresses ? why the girl are restricted not to go out of the house late night ? 
instead , why not boys are taught to behave well ? why not boys are taught to respect girls ? why are we(girls )  being punished without no reasons?
let's stop this thing . dear brother let your sister also be out of house at 10 pm fearlessly . let your sister be enjoy with their friends. let your sister also do late night parties. please i request you all to educate your child as well as  your mind and stop this thing to happen. 
from now only let's start "better world for girls " 
let our babies be born in a world where no one knows the meaning of rape, where rape is just a history .

use - #betterworldforgirls and make this our new motive .

text:
october is domestic violence awareness month. nearly 3 out of 4 people are or know someone who is affected by domestic violence. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
domestic violence affects both women and men, of every race, religion, culture, and socioeconomic status. it‚Äôs not just punches and black eyes‚Äîit‚Äôs yelling, humiliation, stalking, manipulation, coercion, threats, and isolation. it‚Äôs stealing a paycheck, keeping tabs online, non-stop texting, constant use of the silent treatment, or calling someone stupid so often they believe it. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
thehotline.org offers free, confidential chat services so you can get the help you need without saying a word. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
you can also speak with a 24/7 peer advocate at¬†866-331-9474¬† or text "loveis" to 22522. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
at the federal level, it‚Äôs time to reauthorize the violence against women act. i encourage you to join me in calling on congress‚Äîthis should be a priority, and they‚Äôve already delayed reauthorization after missing the initial expiration date. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
at the state level, i provided testimony earlier this year in support of hb 30: domestic violence - education and definition of abuse, sponsored by delegate angel. this bill would expand the definition of abuse to include harassment‚Äîtogether with written and electronic harassment‚Äîand malicious destruction of property. it would also require the state board of education to encourage county boards of education to incorporate age-appropriate lessons on domestic violence in addition to dating violence. ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
education is a critical part of changing a culture, particularly a culture of domestic and/or sexual harassment and violence. let‚Äôs educate ourselves and push for educating our youth on positive relationships to #breakthecycle. #itsonus #dvam #dvam18 #supportsurvivors #metoo #empowerment

text:
anyone else feel like they are stuck in a horrific web of oppression right now? perhaps one they‚Äôve been stuck in their whole lives but is so heart wrenchingly painful in the current moment as woman after woman comes forward with their stories?
ü§≤üèø
being a sensitive person makes it hard to stay focused during this time of uncovering a deep collective pain. i‚Äôve been using this simple practice i learned from @tamilynnkent to stay grounded when it is all too overwhelming.
ü§≤üèæ
‚ñ´Ô∏èclose your eyes, take several deep breaths and focus your energy and breath toward your center. this can be your solar plexus, your abdomen or your pelvic bowl.
‚ñ´Ô∏èvisualize what is stuck there, blocking energy and positivity from moving freely throughout your body.
‚ñ´Ô∏èclear it out: pretend you are using your hands, a broom, a rag, or a freaking power hose and wipe whatever is not welcome away. (ok, maybe something more gentle than a power hose)
‚ñ´Ô∏èonce you have cleared your center, plant a seed with something you want to create. something that you are longing for.
‚ñ´Ô∏èbless the space. i like to say ‚Äúmay i have feel whole and capable to accomplish anything i wish‚Äù ‚Äúmay i have the strength that i need to to get through this time with grace‚Äù or simply ‚Äúi am strong‚Äù ‚ñ´Ô∏ècarry on with you day, a little more collected, calm and grounded.
‚ñ´Ô∏èdo awesome shit. be a good person. vote.
ü§≤üèΩ

text:
üö∫she-roes üëë
"she needed a hero, so she became one."
. 
yesterday was international #dayofthegirl -  in my book that's every day! .
it got me thinking about this incredibly bright & loving girl, sky, whom i met last weekend.
.
she was full of life, her caring, curious, unabashed nature  reminded me of myself when i was younger.
.
i was very fortunate to grow up in a liberal household where i was taught i could be/do anything i set my heart on. .
.
sadly in today's world, for all the feminist bras that have been voraciously flung aside, the shadow of patriarchy still lingers like the dense london fog.
.
even in 2018, there's still a gender pay gap and inequality runs rife.... women and girls are constantly stereotyped and not free to express themselves without being objectified.... .
.
the #metoo movement;  98 million girls, globally, under the age of 18 that are not in school and the fact that we need to set aside 1 day to bring awareness to all of this breaks my heart. üíî
.
i implore you, brothers, respect & honour the women in your lives and sisters, be the women you would want your daughters to become by celebrating your womanhood....we are living, breathing, role models for the younger girls....let us show them they are worthy, they are loved, they are strong, they are smart and that they can become & do anything they want without feeling ashamed.
.
 we have been socialized to feel unentitled to our own space, to shrink our presence. to be feminine is to be small and contained. no girl should ever feel the need to shrink herself to be accepted.
.
it all starts with us.
.
let us blaze a trail & set and an example for all the skys out there.
.
happy #girlday everyday! üòò
.
.___________________________________
‚ñ∂turn on notifications and subscribe to my blog: ‚ñ∂www.thejaxblog.com for travel inspiration!‚ú®
___________________________________
.
.

#thejaxblog 
#thejaxtravels
#sheisnotlost
#globalgirlsalliance
#heforshe
#sheroes

text:
i've never been the pretty one. wasn't the talented one. though i had some smarts, i was never the brainy one either. from childhood even into adulthood i've always found myself never really fitting in. i was the black sheep in my family, the weird girl that was bullied in school, and the outcast in church and social settings. i felt that i tried hard to be who people wanted me to be or who they thought i should be, but i could never measure up. i was not quite pretty enough, smart enough, talented enough, connected enough, spiritual enough, rich enough, black enough... well moving forward, i'm stepping in to being me. and guess what? i am enough!

#imcomingout #therealme #findingsophie

text:
hot news
nana patekar keluar dari proyek housefull 4 setelah ultimatum akshay kumar penundaan syuting üòê

aktor nana patekar dilaporkan keluar dari housefull 4 di tengah tuduhan pelecehan seksual terhadap dirinya oleh tanushree dutta. juga dugaan sutradara film, sajid khan untuk penyelidikan perihal yang sama. nana patekar bereaksi ketika berbicara dengan media di mumbai.

menurut laporan media keputusan nana muncul setelah bintang akshay kumar, mengatakan dia tidak akan bekerja dengan pelanggar seksual yang terbukti. akshay menulis di twitter bahwa ia telah meminta produser film itu untuk menghentikan produksi film tersebut, sambil menunggu penyelidikan. pernyataan akshay datang setelah tuduhan serupa dibuat terhadap sutradara film itu, sajid khan. "ini adalah sesuatu yang membutuhkan tindakan keras. saya tidak akan bekerja dengan pelanggar yang terbukti dan mereka yang ditundukkan untuk pelecehan harus didengar dan diberikan keadilan yang pantas mereka terima", tulis akshay.

sajid khan sendiri mengumumkan bahwa dia akan mengundurkan diri sebagai sutradara untuk menghilangkan semua tuduhan dan membuktikan kebenaran. nana, sementara itu, membantah semua tuduhan yang dilontarkan terhadapnya. itu adalah pernyataan tanushree dutta bahwa pemenang penghargaan nasional telah melecehkannya di set film "horn ok pleassss" tahun 2008 yang memacu gerakan #metoo india. nana telah mengajukan gugatan pencemaran nama baik terhadapnya, setelah itu tanushree menamparnya dengan laporan tuduhan.

beberapa hari setelah klaim tanushree, saudara perempuan sajid, sutradara dan koreografer farah khan, berpose dengan nana di sebuah foto instagram. farah sekarang mengatakan bahwa tuduhan terhadap kakaknya terbukti benar, dia harus menebus dosa-dosanya. farah menulis di twitter, ‚Äúini adalah waktu yang memilukan bagi keluarga saya. kami harus bekerja melalui beberapa masalah yang sangat sulit. jika saudara laki-lakiku bertingkah laku seperti ini, dia punya banyak hal untuk ditebus. aku sama sekali tidak mendukung perilaku ini dan berdiri dalam solidaritas dengan wanita mana pun yang terluka‚Äù. #hindustantimes 
#bollywoodnews
#bollywoodindonesia
#nanapatekar

text:
tell your stories. tell your truth. keep talking. get mad. keep supporting other abuse survivors. a year after the birth of the #metoo movement, much has changed and nothing has changed. victim blaming is on the rise again having seen and experienced it myself from fans, friends, and other people @adamcroasdell has enlisted towards myself and his other victims shows me how malicious and unsafe this world can be for victims. using young impressionable fans to shame and silence his victims shows how far we have to go to make victims feel safe from these abusers. actions from them and him is #whyididntreport on top of living in fear of him and their threats. my silence gave him a thirst for more and younger victims. i realize and know wholeheartedly he will never stop. his fans, friends, and family are his accomplices by victim shaming and he shows no remorse for the pain he causes he feels proud. in other words, if you‚Äôre waiting for them to make an apology, forget it. these men might regret getting caught. but expressing true remorse about the damage they caused isn‚Äôt forthcoming. what most of them haven‚Äôt lost is the conviction that since they are either celebrities, men in power from business to political power they have the right to treat women as they please, not the women we are to bow down live with the nightmare. i decided to no longer suffer in silence but men like adam croasdell we stand up to or say no to feel they are the real victims and, as such, do not need to change their behavior and continue the cycle of abuse making it worse and enlist others to abuse their victims. adam croasdell is one of the many men during the #metoo era included in some of the most shameful chapters in the history of the united states because it shows his complicity and what men of his caliber will do to hurt women and hide it. 
#nomore #speakupagainstadamcroasdell

text:
words cannot express how proud i am of my friend and business partner betsy. 
ladies, we need to share our stories and speak our truth... even when your voice shakes. 
vulnerability is not weakness. it‚Äôs the exact opposite. only the strongest among us will dare to speak in the face of opposition, judgment, recrimination or even hate. 
what does it mean to stand in your truth?

it is easy, when things feel hard or insurmountable, to hide behind our stories. 
we end up presenting only a part of ourselves to the world, the part that we think the world wants to hear or the one that "makes sense". but is that really enough?

in today's solo episode, betsy is sitting down to share her story‚Äîher true story‚Äînot the story she's hidden behind for the last 20 years.

it's the story that has shaped who she is, how she shows up in the world and illustrates that when you stand in your truth, you have the power to rewrite old stories and transform your life. .
============= .
.
here‚Äôs what you‚Äôll learn in this episode: .
.
üíú the story that betsy hid behind up until today [ 5:40 ] .
.
üíé what we can do when women boldly open up and share their truth [ 6:57 ] .
.
üíú how betsy‚Äôs story influences her actions in business every day [ 11:01 ] .
.
click the link in bio to listen to today‚Äôs powerful podcast episode. 
and if you feel called to, i invite you to share this post with any women you love: friend, sister, mother, daugther. .
.

if even one women can heal from hearing this, then it‚Äôs worth asking and it‚Äôs worth sharing.

text:
it's #blackfriday. (check out @glennondoyle for more details.)
.
it's a dark time in our country. it's confusing and there's more grey area than ever.
.
i'm not perfect but i stand for what is right. i stand for women. i stand for people of color. i stand for lgbtqi+. i stand for students; all of my students.
.
you know how we holler at celebrities to use their platform for good? well, we as teachers have a platform too, and we need to do the same.
.
i love my students and they love me. the relationships we build are the foundation of everything we can do in school. it's more important to teach the child then to teach the subject, and that includes having a classroom where everyone is welcomed and loved. üíú

nigerian author and renowned feminist chimamanda ngozi adichie spoke at the frankfurt book fair on tuesday and touched on the #metoo movement.
.
adichie said at the opening of the world‚Äôs biggest publishing event:
.
all over the world today, women are speaking up. their stories are still not really heard.

women are still invisible. women‚Äôs experiences are still invisible.
.
a year after the #metoo movement went viral and ignited a global discussion about sexual harassment, adichie said there was much work left to be done.
.
it is time for us to pay more than lip service to the fact that women‚Äôs stories are for everyone.

text: you couldn‚Äôt tell but it is sunny in milan. it was such an honour to be with @gucci today and listen to some young creative leaders talk about grassroots activism and whether there is ever space for brands within that. the panel was raw and honest and i couldnt be more shocked and delighted to be directing something special here too. after coming back to europe, i was so haunted by the happenings of the supreme court in america. with #metoo, it felt like the old systems were just regurgitating and reproducing themselves for all to see. today, i felt a little starstruck to hear the humility and heartfeltness that @sarahchadwick.k one of the founders of @marchforourlives carries herself with. the future doesn‚Äôt have to ruined if we responsibly listen and fight back against it. i realised the old systems can run scared if we enable different voices to keep challenging the system together and remind ourselves that we, hopefully, are seeing the dying screams of old ideas. from understanding white privilege to @tanyacompas talking about representation of queer black women and the youth, i‚Äôve never been so awestruck and delighted to be standing with some amazing humans. @chimeforchange

text:
i think almost every woman (if not all) can admit we have at one point in our lives been sexually assaulted. 
i was 15 working in a pizzeria, my first ever job. i was one of only two women working there. sexual jokes were normal for them. i wore shorts on the first day because it was hot outside so i knew it would be hot in the kitchen, that‚Äôs when the harassment started. from that point on i wore pants, but the harassment continued. then one day i walked into the walk in cooler where my manager followed behind, and when i bent over to pick up a bag of cheese, he grabbed my hips and humped me. he had to be in his late 30‚Äôs. at that point, i quit, i called my dad and i waited outside until my dad picked me up.

i was 15. and there are more that‚Äôs happened since then. but this is the one i‚Äôve saved in my memory box. this is not okay. this has never been okay. we need to protect our daughters, we need to teach our sons, we need to start a conversation. #sexualassualt #sexualabuse #survivor #youniquefoundation #nomore #metoo

text:
i often hear victims of domestic abuse telling me why they ‚Äúcan‚Äôt‚Äù leave.  one of the most common reasons is: children. ‚Äúbut the kids...‚Äù ‚Äúwe have kids...‚Äù
let me put another spin on this for you. the two questions i always follow up with....let these sink in, please.
‚Ä¢ would you want your son to treat his spouse this way?
‚Ä¢ would you be okay with your daughter being treated this way?

text:
in a move that came as a complete shocker and also an eye-opener to the film fraternity, superstar akshay kumar has decided to cancel the shooting of his upcoming film "housefull 4"

other day three different women have accused director-producer sajid khan of sexual harassment, while he's preparing from the shooting of housefull 4 that will resume today. and then we have actor nana patekar playing a crucial role in this film and he is also facing sexual harassment case from heroine tanushree dutta. 
informing about the cancellation of the shoot, akshay said, "i've just landed back in the country last night and reading all the news has been very disturbing. i've requested the producers of housefull 4 to cancel the shoot until further investigation.". adding more about #metoo movement, he said, "this is something that requires stringent action. i will not work with any proven offenders and all those who have been subjugated to harassment should be heard and given the justice they deserve". reacting on the same, director-producer sajid khan tweeted, "in the wake of the allegations against me & the pressure being put on my family, my producer n the stars of my film houseful4, i must take the moral responsibility of stepping down from my directorial post, till the time i can allay the allegations and prove the truth.. i request my friends in the media to kindly not pass judgment till the truth is out". housefull 4 has popular telugu heroines like kriti sanon, kriti kharbanda and pooja hegde in the leads alongside akshay kumar and ritesh deshmukh.¬†
#akshaykumar #sajidkhan .

text:
many of you have been expressing how much #yourstorymedicine is bringing up emotionally/spiritually/physically. these past two weeks have been especially difficult for folks who are survivors, but now more than ever is the time for us to remind each other of our worth. i recently shared #survivorloveletter, a campaign started by my friend @taniikeda three years ago - and since then it has taken a life of its own. a beautiful mural honoring this movement was just completed in new york, and tani will now be road tripping cross country back to los angeles while sharing more letters in public spaces to reach and inspire more survivors.

are you interested in being a part of this movement? if so, share 1-3 lines (short!) in the comments below.  your words will be converted into an art installation rippled across the us. üé®  @survivor.love.letter 
think of how many people are afraid to speak up and share their story right now, but it doesn‚Äôt mean their experiences aren‚Äôt valid. we will not be silenced. üíï #ibelieveyou #metoo ‚úäüèæ ‚¨áÔ∏è

text:
i love being a woman's woman. i really do. i've been holding this thought carefully, balancing it on the planes of my palm for fear it would break. but it strengthens with every exchange like the one i had with @bossladycreates yesterday, and with others in this fight.
.
.
the destructive trope of the cool girl, first eviscerated for me in @gillianflynnofficial's gone girl, has been laid to rest. the era of the woman's woman is in full force.
.
.
i feel it more strongly every time i discover someone doing similar work. with a like, a follow, an encouraging word, you tell me there's room for me. and my purest instinct is to pay it forward. .
.
come on over. sit with me. talk with me. the table is never full. we create space for each other when we move closer together. .
#thewordforthis #metoo #believesurvivors #whyididntreport #womenempowerment #womensupportingwomen #empoweringwomen #thiswomanswork

(art by @yukoart üôèüåü) this gorgeous artwork comes on the international day of the girl. what i love most about my life are the people in it, the majority of whom are women. my sisters, my best friends, my mother & mother-in-law & grandmothers & obaachan... this day is to celebrate women and girls. üëèüåü i recognize all that women endure, especially women of color, around the world. i commend the mothers risking everything to immigrate, the girls defecting in north korea, girls fighting for education, girls in refugee camps, every woman sharing or thinking #metoo. women‚Äôs successes and contributions to society cannot be diminished, no matter how patriarchal history tried to do so. women, womyn, girls of every color, orientation, ethnicity, religion: you are valued. anyone reading this, we are who our ancestors prayed for. we have the power to support our sisters in our communities and around the world. let‚Äôs make the choice to be inclusive of all women. let‚Äôs make this happen. please vote. and please, donate. @dayofthegirlsummit @dayofthegirl @zanaafricafoundation @malala @obamafoundation .

text:
i am incredibly proud to be a woman. however, i do realize the unfortunate truth that because of my gender, i and other women, are subject to countless degrading remarks from not only men, but other women as well. now, just because i know this, it doesn‚Äôt mean i accept it. i do not tolerate victim blaming/slut-shaming/sexism in any way, shape, or form. because it is wrong and incredibly disrespectful. another thing that comes along with being a woman is the fear of sexual assault and harassment. from a young age i was taught to go in ‚Äúpacks‚Äù just to use the restroom & to cover my open cup at parties. i am not allowed to get into a taxi/uber alone ever, and i was also taught that i had to dress modestly in order to prevent any ‚Äúunwanted advances‚Äù. so, are women really equal to their male counterparts? well, in some things yes, but in the majority of other things.... no. of course it‚Äôs good to teach our girls to protect themselves, but there needs to be a different approach to how we teach them about these issues. when we instill the idea that what they wear = the attention they attract, we are also instilling the idea that if their skirts were too short, they were ‚Äúasking for it.‚Äù this is absolutely disgusting. i will no longer accept this from anyone. if you have a daughter, teach her to protect herself but also teach her the importance of standing with her fellow women in the fight against sexual assault and domestic violence. teach her to embrace her body and not feel ashamed of how she dresses. lastly, we should be standing with women not because of the role they play in our lives, but because we are your fellow human beings. ‚ú®‚ú®‚ú®
men: respect women. understand that no means no. call out your male counterparts who don‚Äôt understand the value of respecting women & their bodies. 
ladies: stick up for each other. don‚Äôt slut shame. look out for each other and respect each other. [ #beautifulworld #quotes #pasttpresenttfuturee #woman #shemustcount #timesup #metoo #cosmos #healthesoul #losangeles ]

text:
yesterday was international day of the girl! i was going to post this yesterday but instead decided today because every day should be international day of the girl, and the boy! as clich√© as it sounds, they really are the future
‚Äî‚Äî
.
earlier this week i posted some stories about me cleaning everything out of my boys room bc they were being rude, disrespectful and messy and i wanted to teach them a lesson. i‚Äôll be honest, it must have hit a nerve with some people. i did get some negative comments  and that‚Äôs ok. we are all entitled  to our own opinions. but the more i thought about it, the more i realized, i have more to say about raising boys!
‚Äî‚Äî
.  this little women, my little side kick, my future crazy plant lady, the one with attitude in the morning and cuddly feelings at night, a true daddy‚Äôs girl who can hold her own with her brothers - she is the reason i try to hard to raise my boys right. by right i mean to respect, understand, appreciate, and have compassion for everyone (especially women). i want them to work hard, learn how to do housework, be amazing engaged fathers, be kind, cook, have meaningful relationships, be ok with emotions,  and most of all be happy loving men and future husbands!  i owe that to them!
‚Äî‚Äî
.

my baby girl deserve to be around that. your baby girl deserves that. i want her to know that she deserve that.  i also want her to know that she is expected to do the same.  she, as a girl, soon to be women,  must understand that what she expects from men, must also be expected of her. we are all in this together and must teach our children to work together, to be a team, to understand and respect each other.
‚Äî‚Äî-
.

we may mess up along the way but, being mindfully aware and at least trying to raise better people is moving in the right direction. change starts with the next generation.  and if that means teaching punk attitude boys a lesson by cleaning every treasured toy out their rooms, then so be it!  cheers to all the moms and future moms - mommin is hard! ‚ù§Ô∏èüí™üèº#respectstartsathome #ihaveavoice
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
#featurefriday nadia murad & dr. denis mukwege (üì∏: ap photos/christian lutz, 2016) 
_______
background: for the next couple months, we'll be featuring global, national, and local influencers who are taking action against sexual harassment. 
_______
nadia murad: 24-year-old nadia murad was among thousands of yazidi women who were abducted and enslaved by the self-proclaimed islamic state (isis). after 3 months in captivity, where she was subjected to rape and other sexual violences, she managed to flee. since then, she's become a global spokeswomen on sexual-violence issues. she has spoken on numerous occasions about her experience, bringing light to sexual assaults in global conflicts. this past friday, she was awarded, along with dr. mukwege, the nobel peace prize for her work against sexual violence. 
_______
dr. denis mukwege: mukwege, 63, is a congolese gynecologist and medical director of panzi hospital in bukavu, south kivu (a province in the eastern congo), an area "which has been blightened by more than 2 decades of conflict" (bloomberg). mukwege founded panzi in 1999. since its opening, the hospital has offered obstetric care and treatment for severe gynecological problems (bloomberg). throughout his practice, mukwege has treated victims of gang rape and other sexual violences. he was awarded the nobel peace prize along with nadia murad this past friday for his work.
(photo credit: ap photos/christian lutz, 2016) 
_______
#onceandforall #timesup #nothere #metoo

me too movement is gaining momentum in india and many celebs from bollywood and tv worlds are being called out as they allegedly sexually harassed and assaulted women. nana patekar, vivek agnihotri, alok nath, vikas bahl, rajat kapoor, zulfi syed, and kailash kher among others are in the list and it seems the list is never-ending as new names are adding up every other day. now reportedly famous filmmaker sajid khan is also accused of sexual harassment and misconduct. akshay kumar gave out a tweet and revealed that he won't continue the shoot of housefull 4 amid the allegations on sajid khan who is the helmer of the movie

many celebs have commented on the ongoing metoo movement and sanaya irani, the famous tv star has also commented on the same. she took to the instagram story to share the story of sajid khan and wrote how this needs to happen and she also mentioned hashtags timesup and metoo‚Äù #metoo #timesup
.
.
.

text:
lady dysp breaks silence, accuses former dir vigilance of ‚Äòsexual harassment‚Äô
jammu: former director, vigilance and retired ips officer, alok pur is another name floating on the internet since the recent eruption of the #metoo movement in india.
deputy superintendent of police (dysp) shashi thakur has taken to twitter‚Äîcomplaining against alleged ‚Äúsexual harassment‚Äù by then director vigilance. 1984 ips batch officer, puri retired as adgp (crime) in jammu and kashmir.
‚Äúi raised voice against land mafia in my state (j&k) but had to face sexual harassment in the hands of then director vigilance alok puri. despite complaints against him that filed no one took action against him,‚Äù dysp thakur wrote on twitter triggering a debate about safety of women in workspace.
‚Äúwaiting for justice,‚Äù she wrote at the end, while hoping for justice under governor satyal paul malik‚Äôs rule in jammu and kashmir.
#metoo campaign has gained strength in society especially after women came forward to openly speak up against their harassers, while seeking justice.
dysp thakur, told rising kashmir that she is being harassed from last seven years and justice has yet not delivered. ‚Äúi made a complaint but then director vigilance alok puri remained unpunished despite complaint at the chief vigilance commission‚Äôs office. they too, wrote to alok puri asking him to look into the issue. the issue was dumped, later,‚Äù she alleged.
the aggrieved lady officer said that she raised voice against the encroachment on state land in sunjwan. the encroachment was facilitated by the revenue department and local police. even as vigilance filed a report recommending fir in the case after three years of investigation, then director vigilance did not file the fir.‚Äù
dysp said ‚Äúsince i was pursuing the case, i went to meet then director vigilance alok puri and requested him to file fir as recommended by the vigilance. but he was reluctant.‚Äù
instead of doing his job, she claimed ‚Äúalok puri directly asked me for sexual favour. but, i declined and came out of his office.‚Äù
‚Äúif you (thakur) want fir in the case, then you have to compromise with me,‚Äù the dysp thakur quoted alok puri as saying. she said the file was on his

text:
friday's prompt is social/current affairs
.
what gets taken away at the moment a line is crossed? in my case the first time an incident of molestation happened i was too young to comprehend, let alone resist. for many years i locked it away in my mind, impervious to its effects. the second time it happened i was old enough to know what it was, but the laws of workplace harassment were not on my side, and i had to quit my job to go on dole in paris as an immigrant. the third time the line was crossed, it was by somebody i considered a close friend, and in trying to fathom how somebody who claimed to care for me could not understand the word "no", my mind literally went into overdrive and shattered into pieces.
.
the past few days with their outpouring of stories has had me by turns enraged, sad and anxious. i'm disheartened to see what a long way we still have to go and how much anger has built up on one side. now that the dams have broken we are going to have to navigate some very messy waters before arriving at something like light.
.
let's face it: no matter how much we try to arrive at a perfect communication of consent, it's never that easy in real life. society has done much to create a whole host of non-verbal gestures that are supposed to mean yes when the lady is actually saying no: smiling, drinking, wearing short or revealing clothes, expressing platonic interest, being generous and kind, the list goes on. in my case, instead of asking the perpetrator why he did such a thing to me, i turned on myself and asked myself why i had all these qualities. what gets taken away in the moment is more than just trust, but your very idea of your self, which comes undone as you begin to question everything.
.
becoming whole again can take years but the first step towards solace is knowing that at the moment the line was being crossed, you could do only one thing: say no. and i did. every time.
.
this is a picture taken in rome of a sculpture called the abduction of persephone, now more aptly called the rape of persephone
. 
#metoo #metoomovement #healing #consent

text:
the past few weeks have been difficult for all of us.
but also, we're witnessing a movement. an ongoing, much needed one. 
imagine that. women having found a way around the justice system that failed us, a campaign that was unplanned, not choreographed and unfolded organically, courageously.
and the tables that are turning now!
we do wish that #metooindia finds a place in the deepest corners of the country taking shape from their own forms of oppression, patriarchy, abuse and inequality. 
but for now
this is a collective victory, and it stands for all of us, even those who could not speak up and cannot, more power to you! .
.
.
.
.
.

text:
while giving her speech at the frankfurt book fair, adichie at the opening of the world's biggest publishing event said, "all over the world today women are speaking up. their stories are still not really heard"

women are still invisible. women's experiences are still invisible.

a year after the #metoo movement went viral and ignited a global discussion about sexual harassment, adichie said there was much work left to be done.

it is time for us to pay more than lip service to the fact that women's stories are for everyone.

we know from studies that women read books by men and women. but men read books by men. it is time for men to read women.

in a thinly veiled reference to us judge brett kavanaugh's controversial confirmation to the supreme court despite accusations of sexual misconduct, adichie slammed the tendency not to believe victims of such assaults.

she said: "we seem to live in a world where many people believe large numbers of women can simply wake up one day and make up stories about having been assaulted.

i know many women who want to be famous. i don't know one single woman who wants to be famous for having been assaulted.
.
.
.

text:
the first "experience" i remember having was so young that i honestly blocked so much but the earliest one i remember was when i was around 8 years old, i remember having my first "encounter with a sexual context" that shouldn't have happened. it wasn't until years later that i even realized what had actually happened. for so many the "victims" are completely unaware of what's going on until it is too late. i like so many thought that it was normal passed it on. now as an adult with children of my own i cringe at the thought of what was going on with me then and possibly sooner and i pray they dont experience anything close and if they ever do they know they can always trust me and know i'll always be there to hear anything they say, no judgments ever! i've been lucky to have married a man that is not only beyond respectful and understanding with me but one that also teaches and will continue to teach our daughters to always feel comfortable to speak up and say no! it's always ok to say no....
.
.
when was the first time or last time you should have said no, but had no idea? or were too afraid? or just plane had that choice taken from you? if the answer to that is anything other then never then it too many times and it should never have happened...
.
.
#metoo #hertoo #whyididntreportit

text:
#hurricaneallie and i have been spending a lot more time together. i wouldn't change a thing in the world. our daddy-daughter time really means a lot to me since i've finally found a way to bond with allie. the way she looks at me just melts my heart and all i can see is something perfect.

with all the talk going around about harassment and the whole #metoo movement, i started wondering what kind of world my daughter will grow up in. the idea of her being in a situation where she's powerless makes me worry. i've probably played my part by encouraging "boys will be boys" mentality. more importantly, it's in my control to change that behaviour.

i owe it to her to start being a good role model to other guys and show the world that chivalry is still alive. i will remember to be kind, to respect everyone, to listen, to encourage independence and equality.

#chivalryisnotdead #iwill #daddyenabler #daddydaughtertime #daddiesgirl #beproactive #startswithme

text:
the story goes like this
i:

i don‚Äôt know why i took photos the morning after i was assaulted. i woke up at 6am, about 3-4 hours after it happened, and immediately started capturing images of my bedroom and my body through tears swelling up in my eyes. i‚Äôm surprised any are in focus.

when #drchristineblaseyford¬†raised her right hand in the senate judiciary committee and swore to tell the truth, her testimony became an invitation for victims to speak up‚Äîno matter how long ago the assault, how violent the attack, how powerful the accused or how official the report.

as the #metoomovement gained headlines last year, i remember feeling lucky that i was 29 years old and had not been sexually assaulted. a month later that changed. almost a year later, i am ready to share the images i took the morning after and the days directly following.

thank you for being here.

text:
friday, and i'm reading papers
that i got this morning
talking about stuff- #metoo
and all that, it's taxing
reading the words of a writer
who wrote as if writing
should only be done with verbose.
i hate this piece;
the juxtaposition of words rearranged,
realigned with convoluted descriptions
of lacerations of the psyche
which culminates to the utter abandon
of form, whilst resonating with pompous
overtones as if the scribe who
conveyed the script is clearly in contempt
at the populace who do not
have a clear apprehension of the vernacular
he or she uses to paint pictures with.

i detest these people.
they are clearly flawed. 
not in the syntaxes 
of their linguistic obsession,
but in their desire to appear
more formal and polite.
their flaw is remarkable,
yet they would make you think
they are different.
fuck these people. fuck their form.
fuck their genteel ways.
and fuck their pseudointellectuality.

.

text:
i have an extra smile with all the #metoo campaigns in our country.
kudos to all the girls who have the courage to call a spade a spade, albeit a bit late but it‚Äôs never too late.
while the wave is quite a tumultuous affair for the film fraternity - harassment is rampant in every sector. right from education to politics to medicine to it. even the home is not safe.
i urge women to push away the shackles of being a victim  or feel ashamed - we have the power to pull down the criminals and stop many from being victimised.
.
it‚Äôs a shout-out to all the sanskari men who felt, men must grope, must rape, must abuse, must torture females. what gives you this power? is it because they are born with a tissue dangling between their two legs?
it‚Äôs a shout-out to the owners of that vulnerable tissue - live and let live - else get ready to be hurt where it really hurts.
.
it‚Äôs a shout-out to those men who have not grown up in their mind - beware, it won‚Äôt take long for the oppressed victims much time to open up and show you what it takes to be a victim.
.
there is a part of he in every she!
let not the shhhhh in women make you think she is weak.
forget not, if she can bear pain - she can inflict pain too.
let there be peace.
let there be respect.
.
my entry to festive mood in my off white  noil saree from  @nextiles  i had to have a bit of devi on me and there goes the hand painted and hand made necklace.
.
#sareelove #sareenme #sareesisterhood #whitenred #weavesofindia

text: this is mental health awareness week!  i was always raised to search for the answers to happiness outside of myself.  society teaches us this from a young age, commercials, music, all of social media points to happiness is something we have to acquire.  the wait is over my friends!  the great news is that we were born to actually be our own true beloved and until we learn this completely, we go from relationship to relationship, one addiction to another looking for love.  once we learn that our true beloved is within and learn to fall in love with who we are, then we begin to attract others that are not so needy.  this results in relationships where we can play and have fun together!  being sober was a way to stop the madness inside and the chaos i kept my life in long enough to begin this courageous journey.  yes i am a recovering alcoholic and always will be, and yes whatever the doctors say to the insurance companies to help me with any mid firings i may have in my brain are needed. i learned that the diagnoses are none of my business and do not define me today.  i just show up and do not abuse any meds, take them exactly as prescribed and my life is so simple instead of me playing doctor.  today i am humble enough to stay on my meds for my sake and my family‚Äôs sake.  i know what goes on in my head when i don‚Äôt take them and it is not acceptable to me.  if you have meds, take them, yet remember that they are to help you, not hurt you.  they do not define you. mental illness is real, yet it need not define you.  i have worked hard to be healthy in sobriety and i will not allow anyone to limit me or label me.  #soberwomen #aa #onedayatatime #attitudeofgratitude #billw #mentalhealthawareness #sobrietyrocks #sobrietyforwomen #mentalhealth #metoo #timesup #metooneveryou #believeher #sexualtrauma #traumahealing #recoveryispossible #theshamelesswarrior

i have been so busy with work, life, and dealing with a similar situation that i am barely getting caught up on what‚Äôs been going on with our country. the timing in this is mind blowing, but that‚Äôs for another day. any person (& not just women) who have experienced something like this just knows she was telling the truth. you can see, feel and hear it from her. and if that isn‚Äôt enough, you can see, feel and hear the lies from him. you can catch the tiny itty bitty smirks that accidentally slipped out for half a second on his face. i can go on and on.. but we all know. .
.
usually for a business/professional page, it would be best to avoid politics and/or something like this. but it‚Äôs 2018, i am a woman, a warrior, and a minority.. i can do anything i want. so if discussing an uncomfortable topic and exposing reality so that survivors & warriors no longer are hushed and predators & monsters can feel uncomfortable, unsafe, & exposed - then i‚Äôm all for it. times are changing, the fight is nonstop. our current leadership is proof of how they will try to remain in power and hush us.. but the future when this will no longer be tolerated, excused, or paid off is getting closer and closer. we just have to keep fighting, more will continue to standup & make a difference.

the full love letter will touch you so deeply. i encourage all to read it and sign it. i‚Äôll keep the link in my bio temporarily so you can easily access it. #drfordloveletter #metoo .
.
.

this letter is our love offering to her so that she has a constant reminder that there is enormous support for her and other survivors like her. we heard her. we saw her. and we believed her.

see the full letter to dr. blasey ford and add your signature via the link in our bio.

our women need us now because time's up!

now, l hope degratory comments on someone's gender, physical appearances and skin colour will also be refrained.
